title: For Sale/Trade:  Custom Savage 243 (Model 10)
postcontent: Pictures show it all:  this custom Savage Sporter has a new 22" barrel and stock installed around Savage's premier short-action- the Model 10.  All work is done to factory specs (or better) and several custom features were also added.This gun started when I ended up with a new spare barrel (off a Savage Axis take-off from another build I was working on last spring).  I had this older Savage Model 10 with a clean action sitting around; so I pulled the old barrel off it, put this new one on it, and then found this beautiful blind mag stock on eBay (it's not a Boyd's stock- but a higher grade, laminate sporter stock- properly inletted without a bunch of plastic and cheap magazine guides).  I re-finished the stock in a semi-gloss (marine grade) polyurethane I've used on several customs I've done--it's the good stuff.  Then I went ahead and bedded the action to this stock (extra 6 hours of work).I like a light hunting trigger for my (light) carry guns, so I also went ahead and worked the trigger down to about a 2 lb pull (which is still in the "safe zone" for this receiver).  Everything inside the receiver was taken out, cleaned and rebuilt and I used a LOT of Lok-Tite after this work was done to my liking (because the factory adjustment screws on this receiver tend to move over time-- and I prefer to be SURE there will NEVER be a slam fire on ANY firearm I own).  So it would be difficult to set this trigger to a heavier pull without removing a lot of Lok-Tite (and using heat to do it).  This said, I've never seen anyone go to a heavy trigger after shooting a well set-up, SAFE, 2 lb trigger though ;)The magazine is a staggered feed and chambers all three rounds in the magazine smoothly- as it should.  So with a round in the chamber, you have a 1+3 = 4 round capacity.  I set the head-spacing a "touch" tight for accuracy (like I do all my hunting rifles).  So if you use (really) dirty ammo, it might not chamber (but you shouldn't use dirty ammo- right?).  Factory Federal and Remington rounds chamber fine- they fit like a glove.  My reloads chamber a bit snug (as I like them to).  I shot about 12 rounds through this build using a few factory rounds for the 100 yd. target sight-in.  Then, using a 100g Sierra Game King in Winchester brass (.015 off the lands-- the standard reloader's "jump")... this barrel put 3 shots in a 3" group at 300 yards off the bench (with some wind) -- that's as good as I can shoot without my "Lead Sled".  So I know accuracy is better than the typical 1 MOA you (maybe if you're lucky) get from your average hunting rifle bought at the store (glass bedding + a good barrel is the key here- and this gun has both).This Model 10 is Savage's darling short action- it hasn't changed much in a LONG time and like my 7mm Rem Mag (Remington Model 700), it just looks like a piece of mechanical art to me.  I own a Savage Model 110 in a 270 that is equally cool- they are great actions with a design that shoots good without a lot of custom machine work needed (like my Model 70s which cost an arm and a leg to customize).  So, as much as I like this gun (a lot, I spent some time on it)... I got into the 6.5mm stuff this last summer (two custom 260AI barrels came in the mail this week).  So I'm selling this 243 to someone who is going to love this gun (and help me finance my NEW "260 Ackley Improved" customs this winter!). The scope in the pics stays, sorry.  I just put it on to test fire this build.  If you need a scope, I do have a decent, new 3x10 (x 50mm) I could sell with this gun for another $120 (what I paid for it) and I'd mount it and bore site it for that.  But that scope is a touch heavy and I expect whoever buys this gun might want to put some REAL good glass on it-- since it can shoot well out there if you can do your part.  This gun looks like new (and except for the receiver it basically is).  With the very slightest of wear (only found around the receiver), your average buyer would see this gun in the "custom" section of the gun store and not know it wasn't new without looking very hard at it.  I've seen prices come down some (finally) and so I'm pricing this right for what is is.  Go look-up some NEW Savage Model 10 guns to see what I mean- the good stuff starts at $900 and up new (and customs like this can go for more).So there is time to get it ready for deer season here if you get it scoped up and out to the range.  My scope or yours- this rifle will be a keeper for someone who wants a smooth, accurate, (darn good looking)... higher-end rifle with the custom tweaks I've listed (which you can not get under $1k at a better gun store).
